@NODE Description
@TITLE " Description of BeamSolver 1.0 "
@TOC Main
@PREV Main
@NEXT Using
     
     
             Description of Beamsolver v1.0
             ==============================
             

   Beamsolver is a GUI driven engineering application that 
   allows the user to calculate the solution for any of 
   nine different common beam configurations. The user can 
   input (or select) a beam's cross section, length, load
   type, and material properties, and then quickly calculate 
   the beam retraint and shear forces, bending moments, 
   stresses in the beam, and beam displacements.

   For each included beam, a @{" beam-shear-moment diagram  " system "sys:utilities/Display cantc.iff"}
   is displayed on screen. This diagram depicts the beam 
   configuration, the beam's shear distribution, and the 
   beam's moment diagram.

   Using one of several techniques, an experienced designer
   can develop a unique solution for just about any beam. 
   Some beams arrangements are so frequently encountered,
   however, that their solutions are commonly published in 
   textbooks or other industrial publications. Beamsolver 
   provides the solution for nine common beam configurations. 
   
   
   Take a Quick Peek at @{" BeamSolver's Nine Beams " link BEAMS}.

   Read  @{" Important Warning " link WARNING} for precautions on using BeamSolver.


   BACK: @{" Table of Contents " link Main}    NEXT: @{" Using BeamSolver " link USING} 


@ENDNODE


@NODE USING
@TITLE " Using BeamSolver"
@TOC Main
@PREV Description
@NEXT Installation
              BEAMSOLVER IS SIMPLE TO USE:
             ==============================

   1.  Using MENU options, the user specifies beam variable 
       values. The user can input variables such as:
       
         *  beam length        *  beam Section properties
         *  beam loading       *  beam material properties 
             
       Alternatively, a number of beam types/sizes and materials
       are available as standard options from the MENU.
 
       See the @{" Beam Design " link THEORY} section for a discussion
       of the beam variable items. 

   2.  Clicking on one of the nine gadgets at the right of 
       BeamSolver's screen initiates calculation of the 
       forces, moments, stresses, and displacements for the 
       associated beam configuration. You must Re-calculate after 
       using MENU options to change any variable.
       
   3.  Keep Units consistent:
   
       a. Input applied Concentrated load in pounds (lb.).
          Input applied Uniform load in pounds per foot (lb/ft).
       
       b. Input Beam length in feet.
       
       c. Input Section Modulus in inches to the fourth (inch^4).
          Input Moment of Inertia in inches cubed (inch^3).
       
   IMPORTANT NOTE: BeamSolver has built-in conversions based on the above. 
      
   BACK: @{" Table of Contents " link Main}    NEXT: @{" Prerequisites and Installation " link installation} 
@ENDNODE



@NODE Installation
@TITLE "Prerequisites and Installation"
@TOC Main
@PREV USING
@NEXT Usefulness
                  PREREQUISITES AND INSTALLATION
                  ==============================

       *  BeamSolver should run on any Amiga with OS 2.0+ 
          and 1MB CHIP/1MB FAST RAM.

       *  BeamSolver has been tested on:  A1000, A1200, A3000

       *  Install Beamsolver by copying its drawer to wherever
          you like. To use it double click on its icon, or 
          issue the command "Beamsolver" from the CLI. 

   ================================================================

               NOTE ON USING THIS GUIDE (Beamsolver.guide)

     This guide can display a number of  " .iff "  images which 
     should be very helpful to users, especially those with no 
     previous exposure to beam analysis. It is assumed that the 
     included image files are stored in the same directory as 
     this file, and that the AMIGADOS "DISPLAY" file is in the 
     SYS:utilities directory. If you wish to use a different 
     display program you can do so by loading this file into your 
     favorite text editor and replacing all occurrences of the 
     string "SYS:utilities/Display" with the full path/filename 
     of your preferred image viewer.

   =================================================================
     
   BACK: @{" Table of Contents " link Main}    NEXT: @{" Usefulness of BeamSolver " link usefulness} 
@ENDNODE



@NODE Usefulness
@TITLE "Usefulness of BeamSolver"
@TOC Main
@PREV Installation
@NEXT BEAMS

                WHAT CAN BEAMSOLVER BE USED FOR?     
                ================================	


   DEFINITION: A beam, in general, is a structural member 
   subjected to loads that act laterally to its longitudinal
   axis.

   Beams are all around us in everyday life.

   Stop signs and telephone poles are cantilevered beams. So is 
   a flagpole...or a tree.

   Most of the piping in your basement can be viewed as a series 
   of simple beams. The same goes for your typical post and rail 
   fences...or a child's swing set.

   Rafters in your floors and ceilings act as beam elements.

   The drive shaft of your car is, among other things, a beam, 
   and the bumpers on your car will more than likely act as 
   beams at least once in their life. 

   Bridge spans - from that big ole pine tree spanning the creek 
   to the Golden Gate Bridge - act as beams.

   ============================================================
     BeamSolver can be used to design and analyze a structure, 
     element, or component for which a simple beam analogy 
     can be drawn.
   ============================================================

   If you so desire, you can use BeamSolver to design your 
   flagpole, or maybe a chin-up bar to go in your garage.

   Perhaps you want to design a new copper tubing layout in 
   your basement.

   You may be traveling in high company if you do. Even in this 
   era of highly sophisticated computer technology, simple beam 
   analysis is still routinely used as an effective tool in 
   structural and mechanical engineering. 

   It is used to design piping system layouts in nuclear power 
   plants, fossil fuel power plants, and petrochemical 
   installations. 

   It is often used to design the pipe support structures for  
   piping systems, as well, and may even be used to design the 
   building steel framework itself.

   Simple beam theory is still used for design of rotating 
   shafts, and equipment and equipment foundations.
 
   An experienced designer can use simple beam analysis to
   design components that are subjected to various type of 
   loading such as:

         *  Deadweight
         *  Thermal expansion
         *  Various types of vibrations
         *  Wind or snow loads
         *  Applied displacements
         *  Fluid dynamics


BACK: @{" Table of Contents " link Main}    NEXT: @{" BeamSolver's Nine Beams " link BEAMS} 
@ENDNODE


@NODE BEAMS
@TITLE "BeamSolver's Nine Beams"
@TOC Main
@PREV Usefulness
@NEXT Warning

               BeamSolver's Nine Beams
               =======================

At present, BeamSolver provides the solution for nine
different beams. See the @{" Beam Design " link THEORY} section for discussion
of beam load types and boundary conditions.

*  CANTILEVER BEAMS have one end fixed and the other end free.
      w/concentrated load at the free end     @{" Cant (c)  " system "sys:utilities/Display cantc_card.iff"}
      w/uniform load on  the entire beam      @{" Cant (u)  " system "sys:utilities/Display cantu_card.iff"}


*  FIXED-FIXED BEAMS have both ends fixed.
      w/concentrated load at the center       @{" f-f (c)   " system "sys:utilities/Display ffc_card.iff"}
      w/uniform load on the entire beam       @{" f-f (u)   " system "sys:utilities/Display ffu_card.iff"}


*  FIXED-SIMPLE BEAMS have one end fixed, the other simply supported.
      w/concentrated load at the center       @{" f-s (c)   " system "sys:utilities/Display fsc_card.iff"}
      w/uniform load on the entire beam       @{" f-s (u)   " system "sys:utilities/Display fsu_card.iff"}


*  SIMPLE-SIMPLE BEAMS have both ends simply supported.
      w/concentrated load at the center       @{" s-s (c)   " system "sys:utilities/Display ssc_card.iff"}
      w/uniform load on the entire beam       @{" s-s (u)   " system "sys:utilities/Display ssu_card.iff"}


*  CONTINUOUS BEAMS are long beams that are simply supported
   lengths over the entire length so that all individual spans 
   are the same length.
      w/uniform load on the entire beam       @{" cont(u)   " system "sys:utilities/Display contu_card.iff"}

   BACK: @{" Table of Contents " link Main}    NEXT: @{" Important Warning " link Warning} 
@ENDNODE


@NODE WARNING
@TITLE " Important Warning "
@TOC Main
@PREV BEAMS
@NEXT Shareware

	     IMPORTANT WARNING
	     =================
	                    
         BeamSolver is an Engineering tool, intended to be used 
         by persons who have been adequately trained or have 
         otherwise become familiar with the engineering principles 
         related to BeamSolver. Documentation included with the 
         BeamSolver Software is intended to merely acquaint 
         BeamSolver users with some concepts they should become
         more familiar with. As such, BeamSolver's documentation 
         is not considered to be sufficient training material for 
         inexperienced BeamSolver users.

         Limitations on the applicability of BeamSolver's 
         solutions are discussed here.

         The @{" Beam Design " link THEORY} section provides a much simplified
         discussion of beam theory and design issues.

         The @{" References " link References} section provides references to 
         suggested technical reading. 
         
         PROCEED WITH CAUTION! Anyone who would set out to use 
         BeamSolver to design anything that can affect personal 
         or public safety is strongly encouraged to familiarize 
         themselves with beam theory and beam design techniques 
         prior to implementing any completed design.

        
             LIMITING CONDITIONS FOR APPLICABILITY   
             =====================================
             
    There are some restrictions on the use of BeamSolver or
    beam design in general. The beam designer is responsible for 
    ensuring all restrictions are complied with:
    
   
    *  The beam is made of homogenous material and has the same 
       modulus of elasticity in tension and compression.

    *  The beam is straight.
    
    *  The cross section is uniform over the length of the beam.

    *  The beam has at least one longitudinal plane of symmetry.

    *  The beam is not disproportionately wide.

    ***  Using BeamSolver standard beams and materials satisfies ***
    ***  the above conditions. The user is responsible for       ***
    ***  ensuring the above conditions are met for any custom    ***
    ***  beam he uses. The user is responsible for ensuring      ***
    ***  that the below conditions are met.                      ***


    *  The maximum stress does not exceed the proportional limit.
       (See @{" Beam Design " link Theory} section

    *  The beam is long in proportional to its depth, the span/depth 
       being 8 or more for metal beams with compact sections, 15 or 
       more for beams with relatively thin webs, and 24 or more for 
       rectangular timber beams. 
       
       Beam Shape           Depth
       ----------           -----
              
       Pipes                The pipe size (i.e. 3 inch)
       W-flange             The number after W in the designation
       S-Flange             The number after W in the designation
       Square Tube Steel    The first number in the designation                
       
    *  All loads and reactions are  perpendicular to the axis of 
       the beam and lie in the same plane, which is a longitudinal 
       plane of symmetry (i.e. no twisting in the beam under load).




