@NODE THEORY
@TITLE "Beam Design"
@TOC Main
@PREV Author
@NEXT MATERIALS

                       BEAM DESIGN
                       ===========

   Analyzing an existing beam configuration is fairly simple if
   the beam configuration is not overly complex and all details
   are known. Using published beam solutions, simply plug in the
   variable values and calculate. 

   Designing a beam from scratch may be a bit more complex. The
   overall process of designing a beam requires consideration
   of a number of important factors. Beam configuaration, beam
   material, beam loading, and the environment that the beam will
   be in are some of the more obvious aspects of beam design. 

   The following discussion is intended to introduce the novice
   user of BeamSolver to concepts that are integrally related to
   beam design and analysis. It is meant to be a quick overview
   so that even casual users of BeamSolver will understand the
   basic input required and have some understanding of the 
   program output.
              

   BEAM VARIABLES
   =============

   For the nine included beams, Beamsolver allows the user to 
   vary the following beam variables:

       @{" Length  " link LENGTH}
       @{" Cross-section properties  " link XSECTION}
       @{" Beam Boundary Conditions  " link BOUNDARY}
       @{" Beam Load Type and Load Values " link LOADTYPE}
       @{" Modulus of Elasticity (Young's Modulus) " link Modulus}


   BEAM SOLUTIONS...THE OUTPUT
   ===========================

   Consider a beam that has a known length, material, and 
   cross section. Consider, further, that it will have some 
   load or force applied to it. Based on how and where the
   beam is supported (or restrained), and how and where the
   loads (or forces) are applied, unique formulas can be 
   written so that the following can be calculated:

       @{" Shear forces " link SHEAR} in the beam
       @{" Support and restraint reactions " link SHEAR} 
       @{" Bending moments and Bending Stress " link SHEAR} in the beam 
       @{" Beam Displacements " link SHEAR}


   BEAM ORIENTATIONS
   =================

   Although beam diagrams normally depict the beam to be 
   horizontal and the loads and deflections to be vertical, a 
   beam can be oriented in direction so long as the loads act 
   laterally to the beam's longitudinal axis.


   BEAMS ARE DESIGNED BY CRITERIA
   ==============================
   
   Beams are generally designed to meet some criteria. That is, 
   when a beam is designed, some criteria is selected that 
   the design must satisfy. The beam design is then arrived at 
   by iterative solution, which involves adjusting one or more 
   beam variable and recalculating until an optimized solution
   which meets the selected criteria is found.
   
   
   The most common design criteria are:
   
   *    ALLOWABLE STRESS LEVEL :
        ======================
     
        In this case the beam is designed so that calculated 
        stresses in the beam are less than some specified 
        limit. Bending stress is calculated by dividing the
        Bending Moment by the beam's Section Modulus.
                
        Given a specific beam configuration, the designer
        first selects a beam cross section and material and
        performs an initial calculation. If the beam is over-
        stressed, the designer can choose a beam size/shape 
        that has a larger Section Modulus or he can choose a 
        material with a higher allowable stress.
        
        Given a specific beam cross section, material and load,
        the designer can adjust the beam length and restraint
        arrangement until the calculated stress is satisfactory.
        
        
   *    ALLOWABLE DEFLECTION CRITERIA :
        =============================
     
        In this case the beam is designed so that calculated 
        deflections in the beam are less than some specified 
        limit. A beams deflection is related to its Moment of
        Inertia (a cross sectional property) and its Modulus 
        of Elasticity (a material property).
        
        Given a specific beam configuration, the designer
        first selects a beam cross section and material and
        performs an initial calculation. If deflections are 
        excessive, the designer can choose a beam size/shape
        that has a larger Moment of Inertia or he can choose
        a material with a larger Modulus of Elasticity or
        both.
        
        Given a specific beam cross section, material and load,
        the designer can adjust the beam length and restraint
        arrangement until the calculated deflections are
        acceptable.
        

   *    ALLOWABLE STIFFNESS CRITERIA :
        =============================
     
        In this case the beam is designed so that the beam 
        has a stiffness equal to some specified value. 
        A beam's stiffness is expressed in pounds per inch
        and is a measure of how much load is required to 
        deflect the beam some distance.
               
        Given a specific beam configuration, the designer
        first selects a beam cross section and material. 
        Next he applies some arbitrary load value, and 
        calculates the associated beam deflection. The 
        beam's stiffness rating is found by dividing the 
        applied load by the resulting deflection.
        
        Designing a beam to meet a stiffness criteria is
        not much different than designing to deflection
        criteria. A beam's stiffness can be varied by the
        same adjustments used for varying deflections.
        

   *    BEAM SHEAR LOAD OR RESTRAINT LOAD CRITERIA
        ==========================================
     
        Here, the acceptance criteria is that calculated
        beam loads cannot exceed some value.
        
        The solution here will be primarily related to 
        beam lengths and restraint locations. If the 
        calculated loads are too high, shortening the
        beam lengths or adding restraints will be
        required. If this is not possible, the applied load
        may have to be reduced.
        

   SELECTING BEAM DESIGN CRITERIA
   ==============================
 
   Depending on the circumstances, the designer  will either 
   be supplied with the Beam Design Criteria or will have to 
   select it himself.
   
   Most of the time, the Allowable Stress Criteria will 
   determine a beam's design. In some cases the design 
   criteria may be a combination of two or more of the 
   criteria discussed above. For instance, the beam   
   member may have to meet stress criteria while the
   restraint forces have to be less than some specified
   maximum value. The beam design is complete only when
   both criteria are satisfied.
   
   There are numerous sources that provide allowable stress
   values for various materials. The allowable beam stress
   will generally be some value that is less than the stress 
   that would cause failure (the ULTIMATE stress). In general,
   it is not a good design practice to design beams
   so that they are stressed just below the breaking point.
   There is too much uncertainty, non-uniformity, and 
   inaccuracy in the analysis in the best of circumstances to 
   adopt that approach. It is much more appropriate that some
   level of conservatism (or factor of safety) be introduced 
   into the design process by using only a portion of the 
   maximum stress as the allowable (working) stress.
   
   If you are designing a piping system layout, the piping
   code or the project specifications may dictate what the
   allowable working stress will be. For steel construction
   there are similar sources that provide recommended or
   mandated allowable stress values. 
   
   Selecting Beam Design Criteria is a crucial part of the
   design process. Beam designers should become familiar with 
   the codes and standards that govern the applicable design 
   activities he (or she) may be involved in.  The REFERENCES 
   section of this document and the light discussion in the 
   STRENGTH OF MATERIALS section will hopefully prove to be 
   useful toward that end.
   

   OTHER BEAM DESIGN CONSIDERATIONS :
   ================================
         
   In addition to basic beam theory and strength of materials, 
   serious users should ensure that they are adequately
   familiar with other related concepts that may influence 
   design considerations:

     *  The use of appropriate Stress Concentration Factors 

        Irregularities of form  such as holes, notches, and 
        sharp shoulders, when present in a beam, shaft, or 
        other member subject to loading, may produce high 
        localized  stresses. This high localized high stress 
        is called a Stress Concentration, and the form 
        irregularities that causes it are called stress raisers. 
        Stress Concentrations are accounted for by multiplying 
        the calculated normal stress by a Stress Concentration 
        Factor (SCF) that is usually greater than 1.0.

     *  Fatigue and cyclic loading considerations

        Fatigue is the tendency of materials to fracture under 
        many repetitions of a stress that is considerably less 
        than the ultimate static strength  of the material.

     *  Designs for dynamic loads such as shock and vibration

     *  The use of materials which have different strength 
        properties for different directions


   COMBINING BEAM SOLUTIONS BY SUPERPOSITION
   =========================================
   
   What if a beam has both a uniform load and a concentrated 
   load on it?

   If a beam has both a uniform and a concentrated load on it, 
   the total solution can be found in a couple of ways. The 
   engineer can use one of the methods available to 
   evaluate the beam loading and write a specific solution for 
   the beam at hand. If the beam is a much encountered simple 
   beam, the concentrated load and uniform load solutions will 
   probable be readily available from textbooks or other 
   industry literature. In this case, the total solution can be 
   obtained by what is called "superposition".

   Superposition is simply the algebraic summation of the values 
   calculated for the uniform load case and the concentrated 
   load case. That is, for any location along the beam the total 
   load is the uniform load at that location algebraically 
   summed with the concentrated load at that location. This is 
   true for the quantities: Forces, moments, and displacements. 
   This initial release of BeamSolver does not provide for 
   solution by superposition. In order to use superposition, 
   it is essential that calculated quantities retain proper 
   signs (+ or -).
 


   BACK: @{" Table of Contents " link Main}    NEXT: @{" Strength of Materials   " link Materials} 
@ENDNODE


@NODE MATERIALS
@TITLE " Strength of Materials "
@TOC Main
@PREV THEORY
@NEXT References

	              STRENGTH OF MATERIALS
	              =====================  

   The beam designer must choose a beam material that is 
   appropriate for his application. To do this, he must 
   understand some basic strength of material concepts. 
   BeamSolver's solutions are based on linear elastic 
   design. Beams so designed are capable of sustaining stress 
   without becoming permanently deformed. 

   BeamSolver users are encouraged to become familiar with 
   the following issues and concepts which are related to
   Elastic Design.

   @{" STRESS-STRAIN DIAGRAM " system "sys:utilities/Display stress.iff"}: The curve obtained by plotting unit 
   stresses as ordinate values against corresponding unit
   strains as abscissa values. The stress-strain diagram is 
   characteristic of the specific material involved and is 
   used to depict important information about the material's 
   mechanical properties and behavior under load. Refer to the
   stress-strain for information on the the following items.

   STRAIN: Any forced change in the dimensions of a body. A 
   stretch is a tensile strain; a shortening is a compressive 
   strain and an angular distortion is a shear strain. 

   STRESS: Internal force exerted by either of two adjacent 
   parts of a body upon the other across an imagined plane of 
   separation. When the forces are parallel to the plane, the 
   stress is called shear stress; when the forces are normal 
   to the plane, the stress is called normal stress; when the 
   normal stress is directed toward the part on which it acts, 
   it is called compression stress; and when it is directed away
   from the part on which it acts, it is called tensile stress.

   MODULUS OF ELASTICITY (Young's modulus) :  The ratio of 
   stress to strain within the proportional limit.  For most, 
   but not all, materials, the modulus of elasticity is the 
   same for tension and compression. For non isotropic 
   materials such as wood, it is necessary to distinguish 
   between the moduli of elasticity in different directions.

   PROPORTIONAL LIMIT: Most structural materials have an initial
   region on the stress-strain curve where the material behaves
   both elastically and linearly. The point on a stress-strain 
   diagram beyond which the linear relationship between the
   stress and strain no longer exists, is the proportional limit.

   ELASTIC LIMIT: The stress value beyond which some degree
   of permanent deformation occurs.

   YIELDING: An increase in strain without an increase in stress.

   YIELD POINT: The yield point is the lowest stress at which 
   strain increases without increase in stress. 

   YIELD STRENGTH: Only a few materials exhibit a true yield 
   point; for other materials the term is sometimes used 
   synonymously with yield strength. 

   ULTIMATE TENSILE STRENGTH : The stress as which a material in
   tension, compression or shear will rupture.


   BACK: @{" Beam Design " link Theory}     NEXT: @{" References " link references}
@ENDNODE


@NODE References
@TITLE "References"
@TOC Main
