@NEXT MAIN
                            REFERENCES
                            ==========
                            

  *  Formulas for Stress and Strain  - Roark and Young
     The "Bible" for stress solutions for beams, plates,
     rings, etc..
  
  *  AISC Manual of Steel Construction 
     The "Bible" for Steel Design and Construction.
 
  *  Mechanical Engineering Design  - Shigley
     A solid Mechanical Engineering and Design textbook.

  *  Elements of Mechanics of Materials - Olsen
     A Mechanical Engineering textbook with a strong focus
     on beam theory and design.

  *  Standard Handbook for Mechanical Engineers - Marks and Baumeister
     An excellent all around resource for Mechanical Engineering issues.

  *  Design of Piping Systems - M. W. Kellogg company
     An excellent, but dated, Piping Design resource.

  *  Piping Handbook - Crocker and King
     An excellent all-around Piping Design resource.

  *  ASME/ANSI B31.1 Power Piping Code 
     The American National Code for Power piping systems.
     
     
   BACK: @{" Table of Contents " link Main}

@ENDNODE


@node LENGTH "Beam Length"
@toc THEORY

   BEAM LENGTH                                 
   ===========

   Simply the length of the beam. Beamsolver requires the user 
   to supply the beam's length in feet. 

   BACK: @{" Beam Variables " link Theory}   NEXT: @{" Cross Sectional Properties " link XSECTION} 


@ENDNODE


@node XSECTION "Beam Cross-sectional Properties"
@toc THEORY
                     BEAM CROSS-SECTIONAL PROPERTIES
                     ===============================

   For the beam solutions included in BeamSolver, it is required
   that the beam's MOMENT OF INERTIA and SECTION MODULUS be known.
   The  MOMENT OF INERTIA is used to calculate beam displacements, 
   while SECTION MODULUS is used to calculate Stresses in the beam.


   MOMENT OF INERTIA OF AN AREA (I) : 
   ================================

   The moment of inertia of an area with respect to an axis "x" is
   the sum of the products obtained by multiplying each elementary 
   area by the square of its distance from the axis "x". The axis 
   "x" must be in the plane of the area. The moment of inertia is 
   typically given in inches^4. It is important to understand that 
   the moment of inertia of a cross-sectional area is generally 
   different for different axes. 


   SECTION MODULUS (Z) :
   ===================

   The section modulus with respect to either principal central axis
   is the moment of inertia with respect to that axis divided by the 
   distance from that axis to the most remote point of the section. 
   The section modulus largely determines the flexural strength of a 
   beam of given material. The section modulus is typically given in
   inches^3. Similar to the moment of inertia of an area, the section 
   modulus of a cross-sectional area is generally different for 
   different reference axes. The Section Modulus largely determines
   the flexural strength of a beam.
   
  
                  *******   IMPORTANT NOTE    *******
  
   See @{" Some Section Modulus'for different shapes  " system "sys:utilities/Display Section.iff"}. BeamSolvers 
   standard beams use the Moment of Inertia(I) and the Section 
   Modulus(Z) for the X-X axis. This assumes the load is perpendicular
   to the X-X axis. 
  
    
   
   
                   BEAM CROSS SECTION FACTORS :
                   ==========================
   
   Listed below is a number of concepts related to beam cross
   sectional properties. Users are encouraged to become familiar
   with these concepts:

    * Principal Axes
    
    * Principal Planes
    
    * Central Axis
    
    * Flexural Center
    
    * Neutral Axis
    
    * Centroid of an Area
    
    * Elastic Axis
    
    * Neutral Surface
    


   BACK: @{" Beam Variables " link Theory}   NEXT: @{" Beam Boundary Conditions " link Boundary} 

@ENDNODE



@node BOUNDARY  "Beam Boundary Conditions"
@toc THEORY
                        BEAM BOUNDARY CONDITIONS
                        ========================
                        
   BOUNDARY CONDITIONS: As used here, Boundary Condition refers to
   the condition of stress, displacement, or slope at the ends or 
   edges of a member, where these conditions are apparent from the 
   circumstances of the problem. 

      *  FIXED END:  A condition of support at the end  of  a beam   
         that prevents rotation and transverse displacement. 

         For a beam with fixed ends, the zero slope at each fixed 
         end  is a boundary condition. The zero displacement at 
         each fixed end is also a boundary condition.

      *  SIMPLY SUPPORTED: A condition of support of a beam that 
         prevents transverse displacement but permits rotation.

         For a beam with simple supports at each end, the boundary 
         condition is zero displacement at each end.

      *  FREE ENDED: The condition of non-support at the end of a 
         beam which allows transverse displacement and  rotation of 
         the end of the beam.

   BeamSolver's beam selection gadgets indicate the boundary conditions 
   for the beam that the gadget represents.

   f-f :  Indicates the beam has both ends fixed.
   s-s :  Indicates the beam has both ends simply supported.
   f-s :  Indicates one end is fixed and the other end is simply supported.
   cant : Indicates the beam is cantilevered (one end fixed, the other free).
   cont : The beam is one of the spans of a continuous simply supported beam.

   BACK: @{" Beam Variables " link Theory}   NEXT: @{" Types of Beam Loads " link LoadType} 
@ENDNODE



@node LOADTYPE "Different types of beam loads"
@toc THEORY
@NEXT THEORY

                   DIFFERENT TYPES OF BEAM LOADS
                   =============================

   BeamSolver has solutions available for two different types of
   loads on a beam:

        *  CONCENTRATED Loads
        *  Uniformly Distributed (or UNIFORM) Loads

   For each beam configuration, there is a case with a concentrated
   load and a case with uniform loading. The user selects the beam
   configuration and load type that he is interested in by double 
   clicking the applicable gadget from the right side of the screen. 
   Each beam selection gadget indicates the type of load on the beam:

        *  (c)  indicates a beam with a concentrated load.
        *  (u)  indicates a beam with a uniform load.


   CONCENTRATED LOADS: 
   ===================

   A Concentrated Load is a load whose effect is considered to act at
   a single point. The unit for a Concentrated Loads is Pounds (lb.)

   A heavy valve in pipeline could be considered a concentrated load.

   A person standing at the end of a diving board would be considered
   to be a concentrated load.

   The user can use the default load value of 1000 pounds or can input
   a different value using the MENU options.


   
   UNIFORM LOADS:
   =============

   A Uniform Load is a load whose effect is evenly distributed over a
   length of the beam. The unit for expressing a Uniform Load is pounds
   per foot (lb./ft).

   The insulation wrapped around a pipe over some length, is a uniform
   load applied to that length.
  
   The weight of the beam is a uniform load applied over the beam's
   full length.
  
   The user can use the default load value of 100 pounds per foot or 
   can input a different value using the MENU options.



   GRAY AREAS:
   ==========

   In some cases,  it may be difficult to readily determine if a load 
   should  be considered Concentrated or Uniform. One person standing 
   on the end of the diving board is a concentrated load. One person 
   standing on the end of the board and another person standing in the 
   middle of the board are both acting as concentrated loads. If the 
   board has people standing shoulder to shoulder over its whole 
   length, that is more like a Uniform Load and would be usually 
   analyzed as such.

   A wind load along the length of a flagpole acts as a uniform load, 
   while the wind drag force on the flag acts more like a concentrated 
   load.

   
   BACK: @{" Beam Variables " link Theory}   NEXT: @{" Modulus Of Elasticity " link Modulus} 

@ENDNODE


@node MODULUS "Modulus of Elasticity (Young's Modulus)"
@toc THEORY
@NEXT THEORY

                MODULUS OF ELASTICITY (YOUNG'S MODULUS)
                =======================================

   The Modulus of Elasticity is a property of materials 
   whose value depends on the material being used. It is
   the ratio of stress  to  strain on a stress-strain 
   diagram (see Strength of Materials section), and is
   expressed in Pounds per Square Inch (psi). Since the 
   modulus of elasticity is typically very large, it is 
   usually given in terms of "millions of psi" and would 
   be expressed like "29.0 x 10^6 psi".  It is needed for 
   calculation of beam displacements.
   

   See @{" Strength of Materials " link Materials} for a limited discussion of
   basic Materials Property concepts.



   BACK: @{" Beam Variables " link Theory}   NEXT: @{" Beam Solutions...The Output " link Shear} 

@ENDNODE

@node SHEAR " Beam Solutions...The Output "
@toc THEORY

   SHEAR FORCES
   ============

   When a beam has a transverse load applied to it, forces are 
   developed  in the beam that will tend to shear the beam 
   across it's cross-sectional area. These forces in the beam 
   are SHEAR FORCES.


   SUPPORT/RESTRAINT REACTIONS  
   ===========================
                            
   When a beam has a transverse load applied to it, the beam's 
   restraints  support the beam by resisting the applied 
   load. Each restraint takes a share of the total load,  
   and the share that a restraint takes is based on the 
   locations of the restraint(s), the beam length and the 
   applied load.
   

   BENDING MOMENTS & BENDING STRESSES 
   ==================================

   When a beam has a transverse load applied to it, the beam 
   bends (or breaks). The MOMENT of a FORCE is its tendency 
   to cause rotation about a given point or axis.

   Bending moment:  The bending moment at any section of the 
   beam is the algebraic sum of the moments of the external 
   forces that act on the beam to either side of the section,
   taken about the horizontal axis of the section. A positive 
   bending moment bends the beam so that it is concave upward, 
   and a negative bending moment bends it so that it is concave 
   downward. The moment equation  is an expression for the 
   bending moment at any section in terms of x, the distance 
   to that section measured from a chosen origin, usually taken 
   at the left end of the beam. Bending moments are expressed
   in terms of ft-lbs or inch-lbs.
   
   Bensing Stress : The bending stress at any point is the 
   bending moment at that point divided by the beams section 
   modulus and is expressed in pounds per square inch (psi.)



   BEAM DISPLACEMENTS     
   ==================

   When a beam has a transverse load applied to it, the beam 
   will undergo some in-plane deflection.  The amount of 
   deflection will depend on the beam's stiffness and the 
   applied load.

   BACK: @{" Beam Design " link Theory}  NEXT: @{" Strength of Materials " link materials}
@ENDNODE

